	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Commissioner Mandelson highlights the need for early EU support</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 January 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> During his visit to the Caribbean at the beginning of January 2005, Commissioner Mandelson maintained that the EU 'will not back down on plans to overhaul its preferential sugar regime'.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> He cited internal pressures for reform arising from the high internal EU sugar price as the main factor driving reform, pointing out that for the EU the status quo was not an option. He did however reveal that 'in all probability' reform would be deferred a year and be phased 'in two stages over a two-year period at a minimum'. This slight delay was depicted as providing ' a breather' to allow ACP sugar producers a bit more time to prepare for the end of EU price support.</p><p> Commissioner Mandelson stressed that 'although we are entering a period of change and reform we are not going to create an open, liberalised market on sugar in Europe. Tariff protection will continue and the preference that we have traditionally extended to &quot;ACP countries will also continue'. He maintained that increased volumes and additional market access 'would have a neutral impact' on ACP sugar industries. He indicated that such preferential access would be provided through the EPAs now being negotiated.</p><p>
 Given the profound economic consequences that changes in the EU sugar regime will have in the Caribbean region (loses of about US$180 million in the first three years, with a recurring loss of US$90 million annually), Commissioner Mandelson indicated that support for restructuring must come into play as early as possible so as to anticipate rather than simply cushion change. Indeed, he called for agreement to be reached on sugar-sector support measures before the Hong Kong WTO Ministerial in December 2005.<br /> </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://www.fas.usda.gov/htp/sugar/2004/World%20Sugar%20Situation%20Nov%202004.pdf" target="_self">Press report on discussions on sugar during Commissioner Mandelson's vis...</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://barbadosadvocate.com/NewViewNewsleft.cfm?Record=19989" target="_self">Commissioner Mandelson urges Caribbean economies to sustain their agricu...</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://www.nationnews.com/StoryView.cfm?Record=56821&amp;Section=LO" target="_self">Press report suggesting that EU sugar reform will be in two stages ( <i>...</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://www.iht.com/articles/2005/01/10/business/sugar.html" target="_self">Reuters press report that the WTO sugar dispute could disrupt EU plans f...</a> <br /> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> The EU's commitment to price cuts remains firm, although the timetable for change is still subject to negotiate with EU member states. Two important points emerged from the exchanges in the Caribbean. First that additional market access will form part of the EU's response package for the ACP and that this should aim at ensuring a 'neutral impact'. Second that restructuring assistance should be given early so as to enable ACP sugar sectors to anticipate change rather than simply cushioning it. If this is to occur, however, then either budgetary provision will need to be made in the 2005 budget or the EU will have to provide first-phase assistance to restructuring from existing EDF allocations.</p><p> An important question which arises is what is meant by 'neutral impact'? Does this, for example, mean neutral in terms of sugar-sector revenue &quot;sf so does this include revenues gained under the SPS arrangement or only under the sugar protoco &quot;lhis is important, for it lies at the heart of the extra market access the EU is willing to give to ACP countries and its overall relevance in meeting the challenge of EU sugar-sector reform.</p>
		</div>
		
